  "prompt": "What is the penalty for driving without insurance in Texas?",
  "response": "In Texas, driving without insurance can result in the following penalties:\n\n1. First-time offense:\n- Fine of $175 to $350\n- Potential court costs\n- Suspension of vehicle registration\n- Potential driver's license suspension\n\n2. Subsequent offenses:\n- Fines ranging from $350 to $1,000\n- Higher court costs\n- Longer vehicle registration and driver's license suspension periods\n\nAdditional consequences may include:\n- Requirement to show proof of financial responsibility\n- Potential points added to driving record\n- Increased insurance rates\n- Potential vehicle impoundment\n\nIt's important to maintain at least the state's minimum required auto insurance coverage, which includes:\n- $30,000 per person for bodily injury\n- $60,000 per accident for bodily injury\n- $25,000 for property damage\n\nThese penalties can vary slightly depending on specific circumstances, so consulting local authorities or a legal professional is recommended for the most up-to-date and precise information.",
